---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";
import NavBar from "../components/NavBar.astro";

const items = [
  {
    q: "Is ShipFlow a server tool or an AI workflow framework?",
    a: "Both. It handles real server-delivery work while giving agents a stronger execution frame through context, contracts, and verification."
  },
  {
    q: "Do all skills work like free-text prompts?",
    a: "No. Some skills treat the argument as plain task text, but others use it as a mode switch or a structured input. That is why reading the skill contract matters."
  },
  {
    q: "Do ShipFlow skills work with both Codex and Claude Code?",
    a: "Yes. ShipFlow maintains skill metadata for both discovery models: Codex starts from each skill name, description, and path, while Claude Code relies on description and optional when_to_use metadata with a 1536-character per-skill listing cap. ShipFlow treats the stricter shared budget as the rule: descriptions are front-loaded, audited, and kept within the roughly 2% or 8000-character Codex baseline. The current audit target is zero hard violations and zero warnings while keeping discovery text under the shared budget.",
    links: [
      ["Codex skills documentation", "https://developers.openai.com/codex/skills"],
      ["Claude Code skills documentation", "https://code.claude.com/docs/en/skills"]
    ]
  },
  {
    q: "What is a skill mode?",
    a: "A skill mode is a specialized workflow triggered by a specific argument pattern or keyword. For example, a docs skill may switch into metadata migration mode instead of normal documentation-writing mode."
  },
  {
    q: "When should I use sf-browser instead of sf-auth-debug, sf-test, or sf-prod?",
    a: "Use sf-browser for one narrow non-auth browser check: visible state, layout, screenshot, console, or network evidence. Use sf-auth-debug for login, OAuth, cookies, sessions, callbacks, tenants, providers, or protected routes. Use sf-test for guided manual QA and durable test or bug records. Use sf-prod first when the deployment URL, runtime logs, or live deploy state are still uncertain.",
    links: [
      ["sf-browser", "/skills/sf-browser"],
      ["sf-auth-debug", "/skills/sf-auth-debug"],
      ["sf-test", "/skills/sf-test"],
      ["sf-prod", "/skills/sf-prod"]
    ]
  },
  {
    q: "Why not just prompt agents harder?",
    a: "Because stronger prompting does not remove weak handoffs, stale docs, ambiguous task framing, or drift between product intent and implementation."
  },
  {
    q: "Do I need every ShipFlow document before I can use it?",
    a: "No. The framework still helps on smaller work. But the more expensive or ambiguous the work becomes, the more the context layer and decision contracts start to pay off."
  },
  {
    q: "Does every Markdown file need ShipFlow frontmatter?",
    a: "No. ShipFlow targets explicit active artifacts, not every Markdown file in a repo. Some files can be officialized later, but that should be a conscious doctrine decision."
  },
  {
    q: "Is sf-migrate the skill for metadata migration?",
    a: "No. sf-migrate is for framework or dependency upgrades. Metadata and frontmatter migration belongs to the documentation workflow instead."
  },
  {
    q: "Where can I see the status of a spec-first chantier?",
    a: "Open the spec. For spec-first work, the spec carries Skill Run History and Current Chantier Flow, including the lifecycle skills that ran, their result, and the next command."
  },
  {
    q: "Does a direct sf-fix need a bug record?",
    a: "Usually yes. A direct fix can stay fast, but if it changes real behavior it should create or reuse a BUG-ID, keep a compact BUGS.md pointer, and record the detail in bugs/BUG-ID.md. Only narrow copy-only, cosmetic-only, or duplicate cases should skip that, and the exception has to be stated."
  },
  {
    q: "Do TASKS.md, AUDIT_LOG.md, or PROJECTS.md store the chantier history?",
    a: "No. Those files stay operational trackers. The durable per-chantier flow belongs in the relevant spec so the workstream can be understood without reading chat history."
  }
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="ShipFlow FAQ | Direct answers about workflow, docs, and skills"
  description="Direct answers to the most common ShipFlow questions: what it is, how skills work, and why the framework is structured the way it is."
>
  <main class="page-shell">
    <NavBar />

    <section class="section">
      <div class="section-heading">
        <p class="eyebrow">FAQ</p>
        <h1 class="page-title">The common questions, without the soft-focus version.</h1>
        <p>
          ShipFlow mixes product workflow, documentation discipline, and server
          delivery. That combination raises the same questions repeatedly. This
          page answers them directly.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="faq-list">
        {
          items.map((item) => (
            <details class="faq-item">
              <summary>{item.q}</summary>
              <p>{item.a}</p>
              {
                "links" in item && (
                  <p>
                    {item.links.map(([label, href], index) => (
                      <>
                        <a href={href}>{label}</a>
                        {index < item.links.length - 1 ? " · " : ""}
                      </>
                    ))}
                  </p>
                )
              }
            </details>
          ))
        }
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section">
      <div class="doc-grid">
        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>Want the detailed version?</h3>
          <p>
            If your question is really about how skills interpret arguments,
            start with the launch cheatsheet for master skills, supporting
            skills, and mode detection.
          </p>
          <a class="doc-action" href="/skill-modes">Read the launch cheatsheet</a>
        </article>

        <article class="doc-card">
          <h3>Want the structural version?</h3>
          <p>
            If your question is really about documentation roles, context
            routing, and contracts, the docs overview is the better entrypoint.
          </p>
          <a class="doc-action" href="/docs">Open the docs overview</a>
        </article>
      </div>
    </section>
  </main>
  <Footer />
</BaseLayout>
